Module #7¶

Melanoma classification with convolutional neural network and openCV¶

Overview¶

This is a multicategorical image classification project based of a dataset from a 2018 competition from ISIC.¶

Here is a quote directly from the dataset provider which explains this data and project better than I can.¶

"Training of neural networks for automated diagnosis of pigmented skin lesions is hampered by the small size and lack of diversity of available dataset of dermatoscopic images. We tackle this problem by releasing the HAM10000 ("Human Against Machine with 10000 training images") dataset. We collected dermatoscopic images from different populations, acquired and stored by different modalities. The final dataset consists of 10015 dermatoscopic images which can serve as a training set for academic machine learning purposes. Cases include a representative collection of all important diagnostic categories in the realm of pigmented lesions: Actinic keratoses and intraepithelial carcinoma / Bowen's disease (akiec), basal cell carcinoma (bcc), benign keratosis-like lesions (solar lentigines / seborrheic keratoses and lichen-planus like keratoses, bkl), dermatofibroma (df), melanoma (mel), melanocytic nevi (nv) and vascular lesions (angiomas, angiokeratomas, pyogenic granulomas and hemorrhage, vasc)."¶

Can't get standard scaler to work with this so we are going to manually do some standardization by manually creating a Z-score transformation.¶

In [108]:
X_train = np.asarray(X_train_o['image'].tolist())
X_test = np.asarray(X_test_o['image'].tolist())
In [109]:
x_train_mean = np.mean(X_train)
x_train_std = np.std(X_train)

x_test_mean = np.mean(X_test)
x_test_std = np.std(X_test)

X_train = (X_train - x_train_mean)/x_train_std
X_test = (X_test - x_test_mean)/x_test_std

Label encoding. We didn't have to do this before scaling since we are only scaling y variable and we didn't scale the y_train or Y-test. Normally we would. This basically is a manual way to OneHotEncode. OneHotEncoder here didn't work well and gave weird results when you print out y_test and y_train.¶

CNN (Convolutional Neural Network)¶

Model 1¶

This CNN is a very short VGGnet architecture. VGGnet was probably the first architecture to stack convolutional layers on top of each other. Previously before this it wasn't done. The nice thing about VGG architecture is that is doesn't have many hyperparameters to tune and is much more simple, but in general goes deeper.¶

I tried Leaky-ReLU but it doesn't have a "name" function so I couldn't save the model. I spent 4 hours training model then figured this out. So no more experimental activation functions and will go back to just ReLU. It also didn't converge well and bounced back and forth in loss functions never finding the global minima. So, what is printed on this HTML file for Model 1 is the VGG-16 model with ReLU.¶

In [27]:
import tensorflow.keras
In [28]:
InputShape = (75, 100, 3)
num_classes = 7

classifier = Sequential()
classifier.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3),activation='relu',padding = 'Same', input_shape=InputShape))
classifier.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu',padding = 'Same',))
classifier.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)))
classifier.add(Dropout(0.2))

classifier.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3, 3),activation='relu',padding = 'Same', input_shape=InputShape))
classifier.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu',padding = 'Same',))
classifier.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2, 2)))

classifier.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu',padding = 'Same'))
classifier.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu',padding = 'Same'))
classifier.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu',padding = 'Same'))
classifier.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
classifier.add(Dropout(0.4))

classifier.add(Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu',padding = 'Same'))
classifier.add(Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu',padding = 'Same'))
classifier.add(Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu',padding = 'Same'))
classifier.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

classifier.add(Conv2D(512, (3, 3), activation='relu',padding = 'Same'))
classifier.add(Conv2D(512, (3, 3), activation='relu',padding = 'Same'))
classifier.add(Conv2D(512, (3, 3), activation='relu',padding = 'Same'))
classifier.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

classifier.add(Flatten())
classifier.add(Dense(512, activation='relu'))
classifier.add(Dense(512, activation='relu'))
classifier.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))
classifier.summary()

Data Augmentation¶

This is used to help prevent overfitting. This will rotation some images random by 10 degrees, as well as zoom in and zoom out. We also have this set to shift images width and height as well.¶

In [29]:
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
        featurewise_center=False,
        samplewise_center=False,
        featurewise_std_normalization=False,
        samplewise_std_normalization=False,  
        zca_whitening=False, ### White noise I've read doesn't seem to help much from my understanding
        rotation_range=10,  ### randomly rotate images in the range by degrees
        zoom_range = 0.1, ### Randomly zoom image X percent.
        width_shift_range=0.1,  #### randomly shift images horizontally
        height_shift_range=0.1,  #### randomly shift images vertically
        horizontal_flip=False,
        vertical_flip=False)

datagen.fit(X_train)

Learning rate reduction helps us converge faster. This gives us a decreasing learning rate to help prevent us from falling into a local minima and to help us converge on the global minima for the loss function.¶

In [30]:

                                            verbose=1, 
                                            factor=0.5, 
                                            min_lr=0.00001
                                           )

def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          cmap=plt.cm.Purples):

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix', size = 21)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=35)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]

    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j],
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True Label', size = 15)
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Label', size = 15)

### Predict the values from the validation dataset

### Convert validation observations to one hot vectors

### compute the confusion matrix
confusion_mtx = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred_classes) 
### plot the confusion matrix

So we set epochs to 5 on Model 3 just to show that we are stuck in a local minima with deeper networks. Upon reading up on this issue, it happens a good bit but generally the local minima is good enough for most models, however the simplier model's accuracy runs higher than the deeper models so this local minima isn't good enough. Increasing the convolutional layers didn't help as VGG-16 had the same issue. Changing the learning rate up to 0.1 (10% change of weights to neurons) also didn't help. It may be due to any dense layers over 128 not being valid as well. One step would be to try a RESnet maybe or another type of architecture. However, we should go back to the VGG-6 model and modify it as needed to get better accuracy.¶

So a learning rate of 0.001 is the max to converge for this it looks like... I tried 0.002 and it wouldn't converge past a local minima.. so the learning rate is really touchy on this model with this data. However, learning rate is also the most important hyperparameter to tune in CNNs so it can be difficult to find the right one sometimes.¶

It is important to look at class imbalance in this dataset as well. About 70% of the data is Nevi class so, we could just guess Nevi and have a 70% accuracy rate. Therefore, we must look at precision-recall scores. One other option as mentioned above is to rerun the model and take out some of the Nevi class to better balance the dataset.¶

def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          cmap=plt.cm.Purples):

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix', size = 21)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=35)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]

    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j],
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True Label', size = 15)
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Label', size = 15)

from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve
from sklearn.metrics import average_precision_score

# For each class
precision = dict()
recall = dict()
average_precision = dict()
for i in range(n_classes):
    precision[i], recall[i], _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test[:, i],
                                                        y_score[:, i])
    average_precision[i] = average_precision_score(y_test[:, i], y_score[:, i])

# A "micro-average": quantifying score on all classes jointly
precision["micro"], recall["micro"], _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test.ravel(),
    y_score.ravel())
average_precision["micro"] = average_precision_score(y_test, y_score,
                                                     average="micro")
print('Average precision score, micro-averaged over all classes: {0:0.2f}'
      .format(average_precision["micro"]))

Average precision score, micro-averaged over all classes: 0.85

"Average precision score, micro-averaged over all classes: 0.85" so this isn't horrid but we need to remember that this was an imbalanced dataset so if we guessed Nevi for every guess we would be accurate 70% of the time.¶

from itertools import cycle
# setup plot details

colors = itertools.cycle(sns.color_palette('tab10'))

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
f_scores = np.linspace(0.2, 0.8, num=4)
lines = []
labels = []
for f_score in f_scores:
    x = np.linspace(0.01, 1)
    y = f_score * x / (2 * x - f_score)
    l, = plt.plot(x[y >= 0], y[y >= 0], color='gray', alpha=0.2)
    plt.annotate('f1={0:0.1f}'.format(f_score), xy=(0.9, y[45] + 0.02))

lines.append(l)
labels.append('iso-f1 curves')
l, = plt.plot(recall["micro"], precision["micro"], color='gold', lw=2)
lines.append(l)
labels.append('Micro-average Precision-Recall (area = {0:0.2f})'
              ''.format(average_precision["micro"]))

for i, color in zip(range(n_classes), colors):
    l, = plt.plot(recall[i], precision[i], color=color, lw=2)
    lines.append(l)
    labels.append('Class {0} (area = {1:0.2f})'
                  ''.format(i, average_precision[i]))

fig = plt.gcf()
fig.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.25)
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('Recall', size=17)
plt.ylabel('Precision', size=17)
plt.title('Stratified Multi-class Melanoma Classification Precision-Recall', size = 25)
plt.legend(lines, labels, loc=(1.03, 0.2), prop=dict(size=18), fancybox=True, shadow=True)
plt.show()

This graph shows clearly that class 4 has the best precision recalls in purple. This was the nevi class which was the biggest chunk of our data. This is also the only class that beats out the micro-average, seen in yellow. Class 6, in pink, is the next best class and they get worse from there. Class 3 was really really bad which is seen in red. We don't want to have false negatives so we want to focus on Recall with our model. So we can conclude that it looks like having a good recall rate will put precision around 0.2 roughly which is not a great classifier but, we don't want to miss on diagnosing someone with melanoma skin cancer. So if we used this model and adjusted for high recall which would lower the precision score, we would expect many false positives as well.¶
